- When a user is on your web page and a click event occurs on that page, they will be added to the event listener as a "target".
The click event listener only listens for click events, not any other type of event.

Here is an example of event listener code for a click event:

```javascript
// On page load, add a click event listener to listen for when a user clicks on any element on the page
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
  document.getElementById('button').addEventListener('click', (e) => {
    const target = e.target;
    // If the clicked element is not an <a> tag, abort the event to prevent undesired behavior (like following a link)
    if (!target.matches('a')) e.preventDefault();
  });
});
```

## Conclusion

Click events are an important part of event programming in JavaScript. They allow us to listen for user clicks and take appropriate actions based on the clicked element. By understanding how click events work and where they listen, we can use event listeners to write cleaner, more efficient code.

